1 Introduction -> 1.5 Data representatio:
{
    "1 Introduction -> 1.5 Data representation -> 1.5.4 UTF-8 Encoded String": [
        {
            "Original": "Text fields within the MQTT Control Packets described later are encoded as UTF-8 strings.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "UTF-8 [[RFC3629]](https://docs.oasis-open.org/mqtt/mqtt/v5.0/os/mqtt-v5.0-os.html#RFC3629) is an efficient encoding of Unicode [[Unicode]](https://docs.oasis-open.org/mqtt/mqtt/v5.0/os/mqtt-v5.0-os.html#Unicode) characters that optimizes the encoding of ASCII characters in support of text-based communications.",
            "Adjusted": "UTF-8 is an efficient encoding of Unicode characters that optimizes the encoding of ASCII characters in support of text-based communications."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Each of these strings is prefixed with a Two Byte Integer length field that gives the number of bytes in a UTF-8 encoded string itself, as illustrated in Figure 1.1 Structure of UTF-8 Encoded Strings below.",
            "Adjusted": "Each UTF-8 encoded string is prefixed with a Two Byte Integer length field that gives the number of bytes in the UTF-8 encoded string itself."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Consequently, the maximum size of a UTF-8 Encoded String is 65,535 bytes.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Unless stated otherwise all UTF-8 encoded strings can have any length in the range 0 to 65,535 bytes.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Figure 1-1 Structure of UTF-8 Encoded Strings The character data in a UTF-8 Encoded String MUST be well-formed UTF-8 as defined by the Unicode specification [[Unicode]](https://docs.oasis-open.org/mqtt/mqtt/v5.0/os/mqtt-v5.0-os.html#Unicode) and restated in RFC 3629 [[RFC3629]](https://docs.oasis-open.org/mqtt/mqtt/v5.0/os/mqtt-v5.0-os.html#RFC3629).",
            "Adjusted": "The character data in a UTF-8 Encoded String MUST be well-formed UTF-8 as defined by the Unicode specification and restated in RFC 3629."
        },
        {
            "Original": "In particular, the character data MUST NOT include encodings of code points between U+D800 and U+DFFF [MQTT-1.5.4-1].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the Client or Server receives an MQTT Control Packet containing ill-formed UTF-8 it is a Malformed Packet.",
            "Adjusted": "If the Client or Server receives an MQTT Control Packet containing ill-formed UTF-8, the packet is a Malformed Packet."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Refer to section 4.13 for information about handling errors.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A UTF-8 Encoded String MUST NOT include an encoding of the null character U+0000.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "[MQTT-1.5.4-2].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If a receiver (Server or Client) receives an MQTT Control Packet containing U+0000 it is a Malformed Packet.",
            "Adjusted": "If a receiver (Server or Client) receives an MQTT Control Packet containing U+0000, the packet is a Malformed Packet."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Refer to section 4.13 for information about handling errors.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The data SHOULD NOT include encodings of the Unicode [Unicode] code points listed below.",
            "Adjusted": "UTF-8 encoded strings SHOULD NOT include encodings of the Unicode code points listed below."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If a receiver (Server or Client) receives an MQTT Control Packet containing any of them it MAY treat it as a Malformed Packet.",
            "Adjusted": "If a receiver (Server or Client) receives an MQTT Control Packet containing any of these code points, the receiver MAY treat the packet as a Malformed Packet."
        },
        {
            "Original": "These are the Disallowed Unicode code points.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Refer to section 5.4.9 for more information about handling Disallowed Unicode code points.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "U+0001..U+001F control characters U+007F..U+009F control characters Code points defined in the Unicode specification [[Unicode]](https://docs.oasis-open.org/mqtt/mqtt/v5.0/os/mqtt-v5.0-os.html#Unicode) to be non-characters (for example U+0FFFF) A UTF-8 encoded sequence 0xEF 0xBB 0xBF is always interpreted as U+FEFF (\"ZERO WIDTH NO-BREAK SPACE\") wherever it appears in a string and MUST NOT be skipped over or stripped off by a packet receiver [MQTT-1.5.4-3].",
            "Adjusted": "The disallowed Unicode code points include: U+0001 to U+001F control characters, U+007F to U+009F control characters, and code points defined in the Unicode specification to be non-characters (for example U+0FFFF). A UTF-8 encoded sequence 0xEF 0xBB 0xBF is always interpreted as U+FEFF (\"ZERO WIDTH NO-BREAK SPACE\") wherever it appears in a string and MUST NOT be skipped over or stripped off by a packet receiver."
        },
        {
            "Original": "**Non-normative example** For example, the string Aðª\\x9b\\x94 which is LATIN CAPITAL Letter A followed by the code point U+2A6D4 (which represents a CJK IDEOGRAPH EXTENSION B character) is encoded as follows: Figure 1-2 UTF-8 Encoded String non-normative example",
            "Adjusted": "For example, the string consisting of LATIN CAPITAL Letter A followed by the code point U+2A6D4 (which represents a CJK IDEOGRAPH EXTENSION B character) is encoded as a UTF-8 Encoded String."
        }
    ]
}

2 MQTT Control Packet format -> 2.2 Vari:
{
    "2 MQTT Control Packet format -> 2.2 Variable Header -> 2.2.1 Packet Identifier": [
        {
            "Original": "The Variable Header component of many of the MQTT Control Packet types includes a Two Byte Integer Packet Identifier field.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "These MQTT Control Packets are PUBLISH (where QoS > 0), PUBACK, PUBREC, PUBREL, PUBCOMP, SUBSCRIBE, SUBACK, UNSUBSCRIBE, UNSUBACK.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "MQTT Control Packets that require a Packet Identifier are shown below: Table 2-3 MQTT Control Packets that contain a Packet Identifier A PUBLISH packet MUST NOT contain a Packet Identifier if its QoS value is set to 0 [MQTT-2.2.1-2].",
            "Adjusted": "MQTT Control Packets that require a Packet Identifier are shown in Table 2-3. A PUBLISH packet MUST NOT contain a Packet Identifier if its QoS value is set to 0 [MQTT-2.2.1-2]."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Each time a Client sends a new SUBSCRIBE, UNSUBSCRIBE,or PUBLISH (where QoS > 0) MQTT Control Packet it MUST assign it a non-zero Packet Identifier that is currently unused [MQTT-2.2.1-3].",
            "Adjusted": "Each time a Client sends a new SUBSCRIBE, UNSUBSCRIBE, or PUBLISH (where QoS > 0) MQTT Control Packet, the Client MUST assign the packet a non-zero Packet Identifier that is currently unused [MQTT-2.2.1-3]."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Each time a Server sends a new PUBLISH (with QoS > 0) MQTT Control Packet it MUST assign it a non zero Packet Identifier that is currently unused [MQTT-2.2.1-4].",
            "Adjusted": "Each time a Server sends a new PUBLISH (with QoS > 0) MQTT Control Packet, the Server MUST assign the packet a non-zero Packet Identifier that is currently unused [MQTT-2.2.1-4]."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Packet Identifier becomes available for reuse after the sender has processed the corresponding acknowledgement packet, defined as follows.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In the case of a QoS 1 PUBLISH, this is the corresponding PUBACK; in the case of QoS 2 PUBLISH it is PUBCOMP or a PUBREC with a Reason Code of 128 or greater.",
            "Adjusted": "In the case of a QoS 1 PUBLISH, the acknowledgement packet is the corresponding PUBACK; in the case of QoS 2 PUBLISH, the acknowledgement packet is PUBCOMP or a PUBREC with a Reason Code of 128 or greater."
        },
        {
            "Original": "For SUBSCRIBE or UNSUBSCRIBE it is the corresponding SUBACK or UNSUBACK.",
            "Adjusted": "For SUBSCRIBE or UNSUBSCRIBE, the acknowledgement packet is the corresponding SUBACK or UNSUBACK."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Packet Identifiers used with PUBLISH, SUBSCRIBE and UNSUBSCRIBE packets form a single, unified set of identifiers separately for the Client and the Server in a Session.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A Packet Identifier cannot be used by more than one command at any time.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A PUBACK, PUBREC , PUBREL, or PUBCOMP packet MUST contain the same Packet Identifier as the PUBLISH packet that was originally sent [MQTT-2.2.1-5].",
            "Adjusted": "A PUBACK, PUBREC, PUBREL, or PUBCOMP packet MUST contain the same Packet Identifier as the PUBLISH packet that was originally sent [MQTT-2.2.1-5]."
        },
        {
            "Original": "A SUBACK and UNSUBACK MUST contain the Packet Identifier that was used in the corresponding SUBSCRIBE and UNSUBSCRIBE packet respectively [MQTT-2.2.1-6].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Client and Server assign Packet Identifiers independently of each other.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "As a result, Client-Server pairs can participate in concurrent message exchanges using the same Packet Identifiers.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "**Non-normative comment** It is possible for a Client to send a PUBLISH packet with Packet Identifier 0x1234 and then receive a different PUBLISH packet with Packet Identifier 0x1234 from its Server before it receives a PUBACK for the PUBLISH packet that it sent.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Client Server PUBLISH Packet Identifier=0x1234 â\x80'â\x86' â\x86\x90â\x80' PUBLISH Packet Identifier=0x1234 PUBACK Packet Identifier=0x1234 â\x80'â\x86' â\x86\x90â\x80' PUBACK Packet Identifier=0x1234",
            "Adjusted": "Client sends PUBLISH with Packet Identifier 0x1234, then Server sends PUBLISH with Packet Identifier 0x1234, then Client sends PUBACK with Packet Identifier 0x1234, then Server sends PUBACK with Packet Identifier 0x1234"
        }
    ]
}

