            "Adjusted": "If a Server receives a Shared Subscription Topic Filter that is not identical to any existing Shared Subscription's Topic Filter, a new Shared Subscription is created."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Session is added as a subscriber to that Shared Subscription.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "No retained messages are sent.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Refer to section 4.8 for more details on Shared Subscriptions.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If a Server receives a SUBSCRIBE packet that contains multiple Topic Filters it MUST handle that packet as if it had received a sequence of multiple SUBSCRIBE packets, except that it combines their responses into a single SUBACK response [MQTT-3.8.4-5].",
            "Adjusted": "If a Server receives a SUBSCRIBE packet that contains multiple Topic Filters the Server MUST handle that packet as if it had received a sequence of multiple SUBSCRIBE packets, except that the Server combines their responses into a single SUBACK response [MQTT-3.8.4-5]."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The SUBACK packet sent by the Server to the Client MUST contain a Reason Code for each Topic Filter/Subscription Option pair [MQTT-3.8.4-6].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This Reason Code MUST either show the maximum QoS that was granted for that Subscription or indicate that the subscription failed [MQTT-3.8.4-7].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Server might grant a lower Maximum QoS than the subscriber requested.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The QoS of Application Messages sent in response to a Subscription MUST be the minimum of the QoS of the originally published message and the Maximum QoS granted by the Server [MQTT-3.8.4-8].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server is permitted to send duplicate copies of a message to a subscriber in the case where the original message was published with QoS 1 and the maximum QoS granted was QoS 0.",
            "Adjusted": "The Server is permitted to send duplicate copies of a message to a subscriber in the case where the original message was published with QoS 1 and the maximum QoS granted was QoS 0."
        },
        {
            "Original": "**Non-normative comment** If a subscribing Client has been granted maximum QoS 1 for a particular Topic Filter, then a QoS 0 Application Message matching the filter is delivered to the Client at QoS 0.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This means that at most one copy of the message is received by the Client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "On the other hand, a QoS 2 Message published to the same topic is downgraded by the Server to QoS 1 for delivery to the Client, so that Client might receive duplicate copies of the Message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "**Non-normative comment** If the subscribing Client has been granted maximum QoS 0, then an Application Message originally published as QoS 2 might get lost on the hop to the Client, but the Server should never send a duplicate of that Message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A QoS 1 Message published to the same topic might either get lost or duplicated on its transmission to that Client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "**Non-normative comment** Subscribing to a Topic Filter at QoS 2 is equivalent to saying \"I would like to receive Messages matching this filter at the QoS with which they were published\".",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This means a publisher is responsible for determining the maximum QoS a Message can be delivered at, but a subscriber is able to require that the Server downgrades the QoS to one more suitable for its usage.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Subscription Identifiers are part of the Session State in the Server and are returned to the Client receiving a matching PUBLISH packet.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "They are removed from the Server s Session State when the Server receives an UNSUBSCRIBE packet, when the Server receives a SUBSCRIBE packet from the Client for the same Topic Filter but with a different Subscription Identifier or with no Subscription Identifier, or when the Server sends Session Present 0 in a CONNACK packet.",
            "Adjusted": "The Subscription Identifiers are removed from the Server's Session State when the Server receives an UNSUBSCRIBE packet, when the Server receives a SUBSCRIBE packet from the Client for the same Topic Filter but with a different Subscription Identifier or with no Subscription Identifier, or when the Server sends Session Present 0 in a CONNACK packet."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Subscription Identifiers do not form part of the Client s Session State in the Client.",
            "Adjusted": "The Subscription Identifiers do not form part of the Client's Session State in the Client."
        },
        {
            "Original": "In a useful implementation, a Client will associate the Subscription Identifiers with other Client side state, this state is typically removed when the Client unsubscribes, when the Client subscribes for the same Topic Filter with a different identifier or no identifier, or when the Client receives Session Present 0 in a CONNACK packet.",
            "Adjusted": "In a useful implementation, a Client will associate the Subscription Identifiers with other Client side state; this state is typically removed when the Client unsubscribes, when the Client subscribes for the same Topic Filter with a different identifier or no identifier, or when the Client receives Session Present 0 in a CONNACK packet."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Server need not use the same set of Subscription Identifiers in the retransmitted PUBLISH packet.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Client can remake a Subscription by sending a SUBSCRIBE packet containing a Topic Filter that is identical to the Topic Filter of an existing Subscription in the current Session.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the Client remade a subscription after the initial transmission of a PUBLISH packet and used a different Subscription Identifier, then the Server is allowed to use the identifiers from the first transmission in any retransmission.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Alternatively, the Server is allowed to use the new identifiers during a retransmission.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Server is not allowed to revert to the old identifier after it has sent a PUBLISH packet containing the new one.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "**** **Non-normative comment** Usage scenarios, for illustration of Subscription Identifiers.",
            "Adjusted": "**Non-normative comment** Usage scenarios, for illustration of Subscription Identifiers."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Client implementation indicates via its programming interface that a publication matched more than one subscription.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Client implementation generates a new identifier each time a subscription is made.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the returned publication carries more than one Subscription Identifier, then the publication matched more than one subscription.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Client implementation allows the subscriber to direct messages to a callback associated with the subscription.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Client implementation generates an identifier which uniquely maps the identifier to the callback.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "When a publication is received it uses the Subscription Identifier to determine which callback is driven.",
            "Adjusted": "When a publication is received, the Client implementation uses the Subscription Identifier to determine which callback is driven."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Client implementation returns the topic string used to make the subscription to the application when it delivers the published message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "To achieve this the Client generates an identifier which uniquely identifies the Topic Filter.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "When a publication is received the Client implementation uses the identifiers to look up the original Topic Filters and return them to the Client application.",
            "Adjusted": "When a publication is received, the Client implementation uses the identifiers to look up the original Topic Filters and return them to the Client application."
        },
        {
            "Original": "A gateway forwards publications received from a Server to Clients that have made subscriptions to the gateway.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The gateway implementation maintains a map of each unique Topic Filter it receives to the set of ClientID, Subscription Identifier pairs that it also received.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "It generates a unique identifier for each Topic Filter that it forwards to the Server.",
            "Adjusted": "The gateway generates a unique identifier for each Topic Filter that it forwards to the Server."
        },
        {
            "Original": "When a publication is received, the gateway uses the Subscription Identifiers it received from the Server to look up the Client Identifier, Subscription Identifier pairs associated with them.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "It adds these to the PUBLISH packets it sends to the Clients.",
            "Adjusted": "The gateway adds these to the PUBLISH packets it sends to the Clients."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the upstream Server sent multiple PUBLISH packets because the message matched multiple subscriptions, then this behavior is mirrored to the Clients.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

4 Operational behavior -> 4.10 Request /:
{
    "4 Operational behavior -> 4.10 Request / Response -> 4.10.2 Determining a Response Topic value (non-normative)": [
        {
            "Original": "Requesters can determine a Topic Name to use as their Response Topic in any manner they choose including via local configuration.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "To avoid clashes between different Requesters, it is desirable that the Response Topic used by a Requester Client be unique to that Client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "As the Requester and Responder commonly need to be authorized to these topics, it can be an authorization challenge to use a random Topic Name.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "To help with this problem, this specification defines a property in the CONNACK packet called Response Information.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Server can use this property to guide the Client in its choice for the Response Topic to use.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This mechanism is optional for both the Client and the Server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "At connect time, the Client requests that the Server send a Response Information by setting the Request Response Information property in the CONNECT packet.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This causes the Server to insert a Response Information property (a UTF-8 Encoded String) sent in the CONNACK packet.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This specification does not define the contents of the Response Information but it could be used to pass a globally unique portion of the topic tree which is reserved for that Client for at least the lifetime of its Session.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Using this mechanism allows this configuration to be done once in the Server rather than in each Client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Refer to section 3.1.2.11.7 for the definition of the Response Information.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

4 Operational behavior -> 4.7 Topic Name:
{
    "4 Operational behavior -> 4.7 Topic Names and Topic Filters -> 4.7.3 Topic semantic and usage": [
        {
            "Original": "The following rules apply to Topic Names and Topic Filters: All Topic Names and Topic Filters MUST be at least one character long [MQTT-4.7.3-1] Topic Names and Topic Filters are case sensitive Topic Names and Topic Filters can include the space character A leading or trailing / creates a distinct Topic Name or Topic Filter A Topic Name or Topic Filter consisting only of the / character is valid Topic Names and Topic Filters MUST NOT include the null character (Unicode U+0000) [[Unicode]](https://docs.oasis-open.org/mqtt/mqtt/v5.0/os/mqtt-v5.0-os.html#Unicode) [MQTT-4.7.3-2] Topic Names and Topic Filters are UTF-8 Encoded Strings; they MUST NOT encode to more than 65,535 bytes [MQTT-4.7.3-3].",
            "Adjusted": "The following rules apply to Topic Names and Topic Filters: All Topic Names and Topic Filters MUST be at least one character long [MQTT-4.7.3-1]. Topic Names and Topic Filters are case sensitive. Topic Names and Topic Filters can include the space character. A leading or trailing / creates a distinct Topic Name or Topic Filter. A Topic Name or Topic Filter consisting only of the / character is valid. Topic Names and Topic Filters MUST NOT include the null character (Unicode U+0000) [MQTT-4.7.3-2]. Topic Names and Topic Filters are UTF-8 Encoded Strings; they MUST NOT encode to more than 65,535 bytes [MQTT-4.7.3-3]."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Refer to section 1.5.4.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "There is no limit to the number of levels in a Topic Name or Topic Filter, other than that imposed by the overall length of a UTF-8 Encoded String.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "When it performs subscription matching the Server MUST NOT perform any normalization of Topic Names or Topic Filters, or any modification or substitution of unrecognized characters [MQTT-4.7.3-4].",
            "Adjusted": "When the Server performs subscription matching, the Server MUST NOT perform any normalization of Topic Names or Topic Filters, or any modification or substitution of unrecognized characters [MQTT-4.7.3-4]."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Each non-wildcarded level in the Topic Filter has to match the corresponding level in the Topic Name character for character for the match to succeed.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "**Non-normative comment** The UTF-8 encoding rules mean that the comparison of Topic Filter and Topic Name could be performed either by comparing the encoded UTF-8 bytes, or by comparing decoded Unicode characters **Non-normative comment** ACCOUNTS and Accounts are two different Topic Names Accounts payable is a valid Topic Name /finance is different from finance **** An Application Message is sent to each Client Subscription whose Topic Filter matches the Topic Name attached to an Application Message.",
            "Adjusted": "Non-normative comment: The UTF-8 encoding rules mean that the comparison of Topic Filter and Topic Name could be performed either by comparing the encoded UTF-8 bytes, or by comparing decoded Unicode characters. Non-normative comment: ACCOUNTS and Accounts are two different Topic Names. Accounts payable is a valid Topic Name. /finance is different from finance. An Application Message is sent to each Client Subscription whose Topic Filter matches the Topic Name attached to an Application Message."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The topic resource MAY be either predefined in the Server by an administrator or it MAY be dynamically created by the Server when it receives the first subscription or an Application Message with that Topic Name.",
            "Adjusted": "The topic resource MAY be either predefined in the Server by an administrator or the topic resource MAY be dynamically created by the Server when the Server receives the first subscription or an Application Message with that Topic Name."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Server MAY also use a security component to authorize particular actions on the topic resource for a given Client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

4 Operational behavior -> 4.6 Message or:
{
    "4 Operational behavior -> 4.6 Message ordering": [
        {
            "Original": "The following these rules apply to the Client when implementing the protocol flows defined in section 4.3.",
            "Adjusted": "The following rules apply to the Client when implementing the protocol flows defined in section 4.3."
        },
        {
            "Original": "* When the Client re-sends any PUBLISH packets, it MUST re-send them in the order in which the original PUBLISH packets were sent (this applies to QoS 1 and QoS 2 messages) [MQTT-4.6.0-1] * The Client MUST send PUBACK packets in the order in which the corresponding PUBLISH packets were received (QoS 1 messages) [MQTT-4.6.0-2] * The Client MUST send PUBREC packets in the order in which the corresponding PUBLISH packets were received (QoS 2 messages) [MQTT-4.6.0-3] * The Client MUST send PUBREL packets in the order in which the corresponding PUBREC packets were received (QoS 2 messages) [MQTT-4.6.0-4] An Ordered Topic is a Topic where the Client can be certain that the Application Messages in that Topic from the same Client and at the same QoS are received are in the order they were published.",
            "Adjusted": "When the Client re-sends any PUBLISH packets, the Client MUST re-send them in the order in which the original PUBLISH packets were sent (this applies to QoS 1 and QoS 2 messages) [MQTT-4.6.0-1]. The Client MUST send PUBACK packets in the order in which the corresponding PUBLISH packets were received (QoS 1 messages) [MQTT-4.6.0-2]. The Client MUST send PUBREC packets in the order in which the corresponding PUBLISH packets were received (QoS 2 messages) [MQTT-4.6.0-3]. The Client MUST send PUBREL packets in the order in which the corresponding PUBREC packets were received (QoS 2 messages) [MQTT-4.6.0-4]. An Ordered Topic is a Topic where the Client can be certain that the Application Messages in that Topic from the same Client and at the same QoS are received in the order they were published."
        },
        {
            "Original": "When a Server processes a message that has been published to an Ordered Topic, it MUST send PUBLISH packets to consumers (for the same Topic and QoS) in the order that they were received from any given Client [MQTT-4.6.0-5].",
            "Adjusted": "When a Server processes a message that has been published to an Ordered Topic, the Server MUST send PUBLISH packets to consumers (for the same Topic and QoS) in the order that they were received from any given Client [MQTT-4.6.0-5]."
        },
        {
            "Original": "This is addition to the rules listed above.",
            "Adjusted": "This is in addition to the rules listed above."
        },
        {
            "Original": "By default, a Server MUST treat every Topic as an Ordered Topic when it is forwarding messages on Non-shared Subscriptions.",
            "Adjusted": "By default, a Server MUST treat every Topic as an Ordered Topic when the Server is forwarding messages on Non-shared Subscriptions."
        },
        {
            "Original": "[MQTT-4.6.0-6].",
            "Adjusted": "[MQTT-4.6.0-6]"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A Server MAY provide an administrative or other mechanism to allow one or more Topics to not be treated as an Ordered Topic.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "**Non-normative comment** The rules listed above ensure that when a stream of messages is published and subscribed to an Ordered Topic with QoS 1, the final copy of each message received by the subscribers will be in the order that they were published.",
            "Adjusted": "Non-normative comment: The rules listed above ensure that when a stream of messages is published and subscribed to an Ordered Topic with QoS 1, the final copy of each message received by the subscribers will be in the order that they were published."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the message is re-sent the duplicate message can be received after one of the earlier messages is received.",
            "Adjusted": "If the message is re-sent, the duplicate message can be received after one of the earlier messages is received."
        },
        {
            "Original": "For example, a publisher might send messages in the order 1,2,3,4 but the subscriber might receive them in the order 1,2,3,2,3,4 if there is a network disconnection after message 3 has been sent.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If both Client and Server set Receive Maximum to 1, they make sure that no more than one message is in-flight at any one time.",
            "Adjusted": "If both Client and Server set Receive Maximum to 1, the Client and Server make sure that no more than one message is in-flight at any one time."
        },
        {
            "Original": "In this case no QoS 1 message will be received after any later one even on re-connection.",
            "Adjusted": "In this case, no QoS 1 message will be received after any later one even on re-connection."
        },
        {
            "Original": "For example a subscriber might receive them in the order 1,2,3,3,4 but not 1,2,3,2,3,4.",
            "Adjusted": "For example, a subscriber might receive them in the order 1,2,3,3,4 but not 1,2,3,2,3,4."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Refer to section 4.9 Flow Control for details of how the Receive Maximum is used.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

4 Operational behavior -> 4.9 Flow Contr:
{
    "4 Operational behavior -> 4.9 Flow Control": [
        {
            "Original": "Clients and Servers control the number of unacknowledged PUBLISH packets they receive by using a Receive Maximum value as described in section 3.1.2.11.4 and section 3.2.2.3.2.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Receive Maximum establishes a send quota which is used to limit the number of PUBLISH QOS > 0 packets which can be sent without receiving an PUBACK (for QoS 1) or PUBCOMP (for QoS 2).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The PUBACK and PUBCOMP replenish the quota in the manner described below.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Client or Server MUST set its initial send quota to a non-zero value not exceeding the Receive Maximum [MQTT-4.9.0-1].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Each time the Client or Server sends a PUBLISH packet at QoS > 0, it decrements the send quota.",
            "Adjusted": "Each time the Client or Server sends a PUBLISH packet at QoS > 0, the Client or Server decrements the send quota."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the send quota reaches zero, the Client or Server MUST NOT send any more PUBLISH packets with QoS > 0 [MQTT-4.9.0-2].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "It MAY continue to send PUBLISH packets with QoS 0, or it MAY choose to suspend sending these as well.",
            "Adjusted": "The Client or Server MAY continue to send PUBLISH packets with QoS 0, or the Client or Server MAY choose to suspend sending these as well."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Client and Server MUST continue to process and respond to all other MQTT Control Packets even if the quota is zero [MQTT-4.9.0-3].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The send quota is incremented by 1: Each time a PUBACK or PUBCOMP packet is received, regardless of whether the PUBACK or PUBCOMP carried an error code.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Each time a PUBREC packet is received with a Return Code of 0x80 or greater.",
            "Adjusted": "The send quota is incremented by 1 each time a PUBREC packet is received with a Return Code of 0x80 or greater."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The send quota is not incremented if it is already equal to the initial send quota.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The attempt to increment above the initial send quota might be caused by the re-transmission of a PUBREL packet after a new Network Connection is established.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Refer to section 3.3.4 for a description of how Clients and Servers react if they are sent more PUBLISH packets than the Receive Maximum allows.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The send quota and Receive Maximum value are not preserved across Network Connections, and are re-initialized with each new Network Connection as described above.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "They are not part of the session state.",
            "Adjusted": "The send quota and Receive Maximum value are not part of the session state."
        }
    ]
}

4 Operational behavior -> 4.3 Quality of:
{
    "4 Operational behavior -> 4.3 Quality of Service levels and protocol flows -> 4.3.3 QoS 2: Exactly once delivery": [
        {
            "Original": "This is the highest Quality of Service level, for use when neither loss nor duplication of messages are acceptable.",
            "Adjusted": "QoS 2 is the highest Quality of Service level, for use when neither loss nor duplication of messages are acceptable."
        },
        {
            "Original": "There is an increased overhead associated with QoS 2.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A QoS 2 message has a Packet Identifier in its Variable Header.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Section 2.2.1 provides more information about Packet Identifiers.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The receiver of a QoS 2 PUBLISH packet acknowledges receipt with a two-step acknowledgement process.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In the QoS 2 delivery protocol, the sender: * MUST assign an unused Packet Identifier when it has a new Application Message to publish [MQTT-4.3.3-1].",
            "Adjusted": "In the QoS 2 delivery protocol, the sender: * MUST assign an unused Packet Identifier when the sender has a new Application Message to publish [MQTT-4.3.3-1]."
        },
        {
            "Original": "* MUST send a PUBLISH packet containing this Packet Identifier with QoS 2 and DUP flag set to 0 [MQTT-4.3.3-2].",
            "Adjusted": "* MUST send a PUBLISH packet containing the assigned Packet Identifier with QoS 2 and DUP flag set to 0 [MQTT-4.3.3-2]."
        },
        {
            "Original": "* MUST treat the PUBLISH packet as unacknowledged until it has received the corresponding PUBREC packet from the receiver [MQTT-4.3.3-3].",
            "Adjusted": "* MUST treat the PUBLISH packet as unacknowledged until the sender has received the corresponding PUBREC packet from the receiver [MQTT-4.3.3-3]."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Refer to section 4.4 for a discussion of unacknowledged messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "* MUST send a PUBREL packet when it receives a PUBREC packet from the receiver with a Reason Code value less than 0x80.",
            "Adjusted": "* MUST send a PUBREL packet when the sender receives a PUBREC packet from the receiver with a Reason Code value less than 0x80."
        },
        {
            "Original": "This PUBREL packet MUST contain the same Packet Identifier as the original PUBLISH packet [MQTT-4.3.3-4].",
            "Adjusted": "The PUBREL packet MUST contain the same Packet Identifier as the original PUBLISH packet [MQTT-4.3.3-4]."
        },
        {
            "Original": "* MUST treat the PUBREL packet as unacknowledged until it has received the corresponding PUBCOMP packet from the receiver [MQTT-4.3.3-5].",
            "Adjusted": "* MUST treat the PUBREL packet as unacknowledged until the sender has received the corresponding PUBCOMP packet from the receiver [MQTT-4.3.3-5]."
        },
        {
            "Original": "* MUST NOT re-send the PUBLISH once it has sent the corresponding PUBREL packet [MQTT-4.3.3-6].",
            "Adjusted": "* MUST NOT re-send the PUBLISH once the sender has sent the corresponding PUBREL packet [MQTT-4.3.3-6]."
        },
        {
            "Original": "* MUST NOT apply Message expiry if a PUBLISH packet has been sent [MQTT-4.3.3-7].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Packet Identifier becomes available for reuse once the sender has received the PUBCOMP packet or a PUBREC with a Reason Code of 0x80 or greater.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that a sender is permitted to send further PUBLISH packets with different Packet Identifiers while it is waiting to receive acknowledgements, subject to flow control as described in section 4.9.",
            "Adjusted": "Note that a sender is permitted to send further PUBLISH packets with different Packet Identifiers while the sender is waiting to receive acknowledgements, subject to flow control as described in section 4.9."
        },
        {
            "Original": "In the QoS 2 delivery protocol, the receiver: * MUST respond with a PUBREC containing the Packet Identifier from the incoming PUBLISH packet, having accepted ownership of the Application Message [MQTT-4.3.3-8].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
